{"chunk_id": "9c1614c5-2a15-4083-9e97-d72ef2508ebf", "source_database": "ICMR", "document_title": "ICMR_NIN_Dietary_Guidelines_Real.pdf", "publication_version": "Latest", "chunk_sequence_number": 152, "content_type": "Medical Guideline", "language": "English", "text": "of our Indian diets. The small amounts of invisible fat present in various foods add up to a substantial level in our daily diet (about 15 g in rural population and 30g among urban middle-income and high-income groups). Most animal foods provide high amounts of invisible fat. The total fat (visible + invisible) in the diet should provide between 20-30% of total calories. The visible fat intake in the diets can go upto 50g/person/day based on the level of physical activity and physiological status. Adults with sedentary lifestyle should consume about 25 g of visible fat, while individuals involved in hard physical work require 30 - 40g of visible fat. Visible fat intake should be increased during pregnancy and lactation to 30g. The higher fat and EFA requirements during pregnancy and", "embedding": [0.006457039155066013, -0.027161257341504097, -0.0016192615730687976, 0.12160791456699371, 0.04443792626261711, 0.021351557224988937, 0.01440660934895277, 0.011136475019156933, -0.07654250413179398, 0.05509166046977043, 0.047486383467912674, -0.12365584075450897, -0.05770257115364075, -0.08488207310438156, 0.07218199223279953, -0.059241581708192825, 0.12437047064304352, -0.0723404809832573, -0.018893811851739883, -0.059801191091537476, 0.11371365189552307, -0.015210106037557125, 0.08357414603233337, -0.0502348318696022, 0.04080912470817566, -0.06611122936010361, 0.01995318941771984, -0.07445766776800156, -0.03851311653852463, 0.027631063014268875, 0.005761102307587862, -0.058150436729192734, 0.042901698499917984, -0.05358332768082619, -0.12078859657049179, -0.010809500701725483, 0.02060410939157009, -0.060517001897096634, -0.027785493060946465, -0.08438186347484589, 0.003574869129806757, 0.008945778012275696